What is an Exception?
An exception is an unexpected error that occurs while running a program. Java provides a way to handle these errors without crashing the program.

Why Use Exception Handling?
ğŸ”¹ If an error happens and we donâ€™t handle it, the program stops suddenly âŒ.
ğŸ”¹ Exception handling allows us to catch the error and continue running âœ….

Basic Try-Catch Example
java
Copy
Edit
public class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int result = 10 / 0;  // âŒ This will cause an error (division by zero)
            System.out.println(result);
        } catch (ArithmeticException e) {
            System.out.println("Error: Cannot divide by zero!");
        }
    }
}
ğŸ”¹ try block â†’ Code that may cause an error.
ğŸ”¹ catch block â†’ Handles the error and prevents the program from crashing.

ğŸ›‘ Without try-catch, the program would crash.
âœ… With try-catch, the program prints "Error: Cannot divide by zero!" and continues running.

Analogy for Exception Handling
ğŸš— Imagine you are driving a car:

If a dog suddenly appears on the road (exception), you donâ€™t crash the car.
Instead, you hit the brakes (handle the exception) and continue safely.
Types of Exceptions
1ï¸âƒ£ Checked Exception â†’ Must be handled in code (e.g., IOException).
ğŸ”¹ Example: Reading a file that doesnâ€™t exist.

2ï¸âƒ£ Unchecked Exception â†’ Happens at runtime (e.g., NullPointerException).
ğŸ”¹ Example: Trying to access an object that is null.

3ï¸âƒ£ Custom Exception â†’ You can create your own exceptions for specific cases.

Finally Block (Always Runs!)
java
Copy
Edit
try {
    int arr[] = {1, 2, 3};
    System.out.println(arr[5]);  // âŒ Error (Index out of bounds)
} catch (ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException e) {
    System.out.println("Error: Index is out of bounds!");
} finally {
    System.out.println("This always runs, no matter what!");  
}
ğŸ”¹ finally block runs whether an exception occurs or not (like closing a file or database after use).

Throw vs Throws
throw â†’ Manually throw an exception.
throws â†’ Declares that a method might throw an exception.
java
Copy
Edit
void checkAge(int age) throws Exception {
    if (age < 18) {
        throw new Exception("You must be 18+ to vote!");
    }
}
Summary
âœ… Exception handling prevents crashes
âœ… Use try-catch to handle errors
âœ… Use finally for cleanup (always runs)
âœ… Use throw to manually trigger an error
