Custom exception
Custom Exception in Java â€“ Simple Explanation
What is a Custom Exception?
A custom exception is a user-defined exception that you create when built-in exceptions donâ€™t fit your needs.

Why Create a Custom Exception?
ğŸ”¹ Java has built-in exceptions (NullPointerException, ArithmeticException, etc.).
ğŸ”¹ But sometimes, we need a specific error message for our program.
ğŸ”¹ Example: If a user enters an invalid age (negative age), Java has no built-in exception for this.

How to Create a Custom Exception?
1ï¸âƒ£ Extend the Exception class (checked exception) OR RuntimeException class (unchecked exception).
2ï¸âƒ£ Use throw to trigger the exception.
3ï¸âƒ£ Use try-catch to handle it.

Example: Creating a Custom Exception
java
Copy
Edit
// Step 1: Create a custom exception by extending Exception
class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
    public InvalidAgeException(String message) {
        super(message);  // Pass message to Exception class
    }
}

// Step 2: Use the custom exception
public class CustomExceptionExample {
    static void checkAge(int age) throws InvalidAgeException {
        if (age < 0) {
            throw new InvalidAgeException("Age cannot be negative!"); // Trigger the custom exception
        }
        System.out.println("Valid Age: " + age);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            checkAge(-5);  // âŒ This will throw an exception
        } catch (InvalidAgeException e) {
            System.out.println("Caught Exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
Explanation
1ï¸âƒ£ We created a custom exception (InvalidAgeException) by extending Exception.
2ï¸âƒ£ We throw the exception (throw new InvalidAgeException) if the age is negative.
3ï¸âƒ£ The catch block catches and handles the exception instead of crashing the program.

Analogy for Custom Exception
ğŸš— Imagine a Car Rental Service:

If a customer is below 18 years old, there is no built-in Java exception for this.
Instead, we create a UnderageException to handle this situation.
Summary
âœ… Use custom exceptions when built-in ones donâ€™t fit.
âœ… Extend Exception (checked) or RuntimeException (unchecked).
âœ… Use throw to trigger and try-catch to handle it.

